{"ts":"2026-06-27T16:00:42.124Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing the Strategy**\n\nOkay, I've got a plan to connect the /portal/analytics and /portal/governance endpoints to their respective API v1 counterparts. My focus is on replacing static data with backend summaries while leaving the landing page and GFF AI tools untouched. This strategy leverages the `localStorage.getItem(\"gff_ai_access_token\")` functionality for access.\n\n\n**Connecting the APIs**\n\nI'm now focusing on integrating the `/portal/analytics` endpoint with its `/api/v1/analytics/client` counterpart.  The initial UI in `app/portal/analytics/page.tsx` is very simple, showing simulated data.  I need to replace that with the data from the v1 API, which includes project summaries.  I'm also considering the implications of error states, loading states, and ensuring that mobile behavior is preserved.\n\n\n**Refining the Display**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on how to best present the fetched data within `/portal/analytics`. My plan is to replace the existing static elements, like the CPU load stream and network latency displays, with dynamic information pulled from `/api/v1/analytics/client`. I'm thinking of displaying this as a series of telemetry charts and metrics, ensuring that the new visualizations are refreshed from backend summaries and governance records.\n\n\n**Visualizing the Data**\n\nI'm now determining the best way to display the data I'm retrieving. I'm moving toward building a telemetry and system summary dashboard within `/portal/analytics` that visualizes key metrics. Specifically, I plan to include the Enclave CPU Load stream (with dynamic logic), Network Latencies, and System Summary panels sourced directly from the `/api/v1/analytics/client` response, which should improve the user experience. I need to make sure I am accounting for summaries for projects, AI operations, documents, invoices, support tickets, and governance.\n\n\n**Designing the New Layout**\n\nI'm now focusing on the visual presentation and state management within the `/portal/analytics` page. I've decided on a robust approach that incorporates loading, empty, error, and retry states. I'm using `fetch` with `useEffect` to retrieve data from `/api/v1/analytics/client` and store the response in an `analyticsData` state. The UI will feature a premium grid or Bento layout with summary cards for Projects, AI Operations, Governance & Risk, Support & Incidents, and Documents & Invoices. I am also working to refresh the existing Phase 4 elements: Enclave CPU Load Stream and Network Latencies, while maintaining a good user experience. I am going to see how the `/portal/gover` file is affected by this, as well.\n\n\n"}}
