{"ts":"2026-06-27T16:01:03.129Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Mapping Governance Data**\n\nI've made progress on mapping the `/portal/governance` page data. I'm focusing on those three lists: policies, oversights, and documents. I'm now digging into the governance API `/api/v1/gover` to determine how the data should be structured and how best to represent it.\n\n\n**Analyzing Governance Structure**\n\nI am now focusing on the structure of the governance data from the `/api/v1/governance` endpoint. I'm trying to determine if a single governance item can represent a policy, an oversight, or a document. I'm cross-referencing this with the task description and mock data to see how the backend items relate. I am reviewing how `gov-001`, in particular, is structured.\n\n\n**Categorizing Governance Records**\n\nI'm now diving into how backend records like `gov-002`, `gov-003`, and `gov-004` can be categorized and presented within the `/portal/governance` lists. Specifically, how do we determine whether they appear under \"policies,\" \"oversights,\" or \"documents\"? I'm looking for a dynamic approach and comparing this to the hardcoded lists in the `page.tsx` file. I'm focusing on the relationship between API data and the UI presentation.\n\n\n**Defining Governance Mapping**\n\nI'm now determining how `ApiGovernanceItem` objects can map to the frontend presentation. Specifically, I'm thinking about how to filter or parse the items returned by the backend GET endpoint (`/api/v1/governance`). I see how we can map each item's data to our existing data model and states, particularly mapping `item.status` to `compliant`, `warning`, or `critical`. I'm starting to build out the logic for handling the different states. I've focused on mapping to `policies` but now I need to expand to include `oversights` and `documents`.\n\n\n**Refining Status Mappings**\n\nI've been refining the logic for mapping backend statuses and severities to frontend states. I'm focusing on handling different combinations, such as \"flagged\" and \"critical\", or \"under review\" and \"low\". I've finalized mapping for `compliant`, `warning`, and `critical` states. I'm also now structuring the governance item mapping, including `projectId`, `projectName`, `agentId`, `agentName`, `desc`, `lastChecked`, and `logs`. I'm also determining how best to categorize records that might be `oversights`.\n\n\n**Determining Governance Representation**\n\nI'm now determining how to integrate fetched backend governance items with the existing static lists, specifically for the tabbed UI structure. I see the tab values are `\"pols\"`, `\"oversight\"`, and `\"docs\"`, each linked to `filteredPols`, `filteredOversights`, and `filteredDocs`, respectively. I'm focusing on the instruction to replace static data with backend data. I'm trying to determine if we can use a single unified system, or map them dynamically, and if we should use both backend and static items. I see the Phase 4 UI and tabs are the key.\n\n\n**Categorizing Record Display**\n\nI'm now determining how these specific backend records, filtered for a particular client, should be presented on the frontend. Given that only `gov-001` and `gov-002` are returned for client \"client-001,\" I'm focused on their categorization within the UI. I'm considering potential mapping logic to assign them to \"policies,\" \"oversights,\" or \"documents\" based on available data. I'm trying to ensure a clean and intuitive user experience.\n\n\n"}}
