g Page Structure**\n\nI'm now defining the structure for the analytics page layout. I'll include a header and utilize a dashboard skeleton for loading states with pulse animations and a premium look. An error card with a retry button will be displayed upon errors. If the data or summary is missing, an empty state card will appear. Otherwise, I'll render the summary cards in a bento-like layout, including Sovereign Enclaves, AI Operations, and Governance Risk based on the provided data.\n\n\n**Composing Initial Elements**\n\nI'm now composing the initial elements, focusing on implementing the header with a refresh button alongside the title, using a flex container for responsiveness. I'm focusing on incorporating the original CSS classes. The telemetry analytics section is still at the top, along with real-time thread spends and other elements. Then I plan to build out the other elements.\n\n\n**Implementing Telemetry Section**\n\nI'm now implementing the telemetry analytics section. I've integrated a real-time thread spends indicator, hardware workloads display, and eBPF network pings, with a refresh button. Currently, I'm integrating the loading state into this section, ensuring visual cues for asynchronous data loading.\n\n\n**Constructing Loading States**\n\nI'm now focusing on constructing loading states for the UI elements, using skeleton placeholders for a visually appealing and informative experience during data fetching. I'm leveraging the `animate-pulse` class for dynamic feedback, and I'm designing a skeleton grid layout for various card components. I'm also ensuring responsiveness across different screen sizes with grid columns.\n\n\n**Designing Error State**\n\nI'm now designing the error state for the telemetry section. I'm focusing on crafting a clear and concise display using a dedicated card. I'll include the necessary header elements and an informative error message. I'm ensuring the error card integrates seamlessly with the overall design, aligning